# hilavitkutin-extensions backlog

Type-surface reminder: every pub signature in this crate uses notko's
fallibility ladder (Just / Maybe / Outcome), arvo primitives for
numeric and boolean values, and fixed-capacity structured errors with
no heap payloads. Path and symbol-name inputs are raw null-terminated
byte slices at the FFI boundary. Collections do not cross the public
API — the crate returns typed symbol handles, not containers of them.

## Designed, deferred

### Hot-reload ref-counting unload

v1 ships RAII unload plus an explicit `Extension::close` that returns
load-status. Both unload the library once. A future evolution may add
ref-counted unload to support hot-reload scenarios where a consumer
wants to reload the same library path while old handles may still
exist. The current API rejects that use pattern by construction — the
lifetime system prevents outstanding symbols from outliving their
loader. Hot-reload needs a different contract (likely a versioned
handle token) and that redesign is out of v1 scope.

### Async loading wrappers

v1 is synchronous. Loading a library blocks the calling thread for the
duration of the OS dlopen call. A future evolution may layer async
wrappers on top for hosts that want non-blocking load. The sync core
stays — the async layer is purely additive.

### Wasm dlopen

The wasm32 targets do not expose a dlopen equivalent at the ABI level;
wasm-component-model is a different mechanism entirely. Extending this
crate to wasm32 is out of scope. If hilavitkutin-plugins needs wasm
plugin support, it lands via a separate transport.

### Capability-level compatibility negotiation

v1 exposes a narrow compatibility_check helper with three fixed
incompatibility categories. Full ABI-schema negotiation, capability
introspection, or feature-flag matching belongs to hilavitkutin-plugins
or consumer-owned contract crates — not the loader.

### Signing and signature verification

The loader trusts whatever the OS loader trusts. Signed-library
enforcement, hash verification, or provenance policy is not handled
here. Consumer-side policy layers that need these checks apply them
before or after calling into this crate.

### Loader telemetry hooks

Counters for load count, load-time distribution, and failure rates
are not exposed in v1. A future addition under a feature flag may add
them if downstream consumers need loader visibility without having to
wrap every call site.
